@ltfschoen It looks like the issue here might be that `interface` is an abstract contract which is meant to be used with the inheritance pattern. Could you see if removing the interface deployments / linkages from the migrations and substituting them with something like the following in your Solidity contract definitions achieves what you're aiming for?
```
import "./Token.sol";

contract TokenRecipient is Token {
   ... etc ...
}
```

@cgewecke After debugging deep what I found is that my problem is not related to Interfaces even if the Error Stack is the same.
Contracts implementation is almost the same as the one suggested<a href="https://blog.colony.io/writing-more-robust-smart-contracts-99ad0a11e948"> here.</a>
So I will use the same contracts to explain.

Let's say I have the Ownable.sol, ExternalStorage.sol and the SecurityLibrary.sol as the example.
The error occurred when I use the function of the library inside the constructor when writing Organisation.sol

`import "SecurityLibrary.sol";

contract Organisation
{
  using SecurityLibrary for address;
  address public eternalStorage;

  function Organisation(address _eternalStorage, address _admin) {
    tokenLedger = ITokenLedger(_tokenLedger);
    eternalStorage = _eternalStorage;

    eternalStorage.addAdmin(_admin);//ERROR OCCUR WHEN I ADD THIS LINE.
   //addAdmin is a function inside the SecurityLibrary.sol
  }
  [...]
}`

Any Idea why this is happening?
Should I open a new Issue?
Thanks in advance!

@violalbi91 I'd suggest creating a new issue.

I found that for the current issue #796, if I only import the dependent interfaces that a contract uses 
```
import "./Token.sol";

contract TokenRecipient is Token {
  ...
}
```
and I remove the deployment and linkages of the interface contract (i.e. removing the following code)
```
deployer.deploy(Token);
deployer.link(Token, TokenRecipient);
```
then it compiles successfully.

I also discovered that in the latest project I'm working on https://github.com/ltfschoen/benzcoin, if I change `contract ERC20Interface {` to `interface ERC20Interface {` instead, then it still compiles successfully.

@cgewecke you are right the contract is not instantiated. I am referring to <a href="https://gist.github.com/elenadimitrova/609418919159bdf80ece48b65a44ad8e"> this contract from Colony</a> where the EternalStorage address is passed through the constructor. If I use `externalStorage = new EternalStorage() ` the error goes away but the externalStorage has a different address from the one I deployed I guess. Is there a way to create a new instance of the contract related to the address where it has been deployed?

My migration.sol is like this : 
```
contract Migrations {
  address public owner;
  uint public last_completed_migration;
  modifier restricted() {
    if (msg.sender == owner) _;
  }
  function Migrations() {
    owner = msg.sender;
  }
  function setCompleted(uint completed) restricted {
    last_completed_migration = completed;
  }
  function upgrade(address new_address) restricted {
    Migrations upgraded = Migrations(new_address);
    upgraded.setCompleted(last_completed_migration);
  }
}
```

